## Feature 1: AI College & Course Recommendations — the core feature
1. Student fills in academic details — 12th percentage, stream, and if they're in the Computer Science/PCM stream, also Maths/Physics/Chemistry marks.
2. If PCM, the backend automatically calculates a **TNEA-style cutoff** (`Maths + Physics/2 + Chemistry/2`, out of 200) — the actual formula Tamil Nadu engineering admissions use — rather than just using the raw percentage, since that's what real counseling cutoffs are based on.
3. When the student clicks "Refresh recommendations," the backend pulls every active college and runs each one through a **rule-based scoring function** — not the AI — that weighs four factors: academic eligibility (40%), category/subject match (25%), college type + state preference (15%), and budget fit (20%).
4. Each factor produces a 0–1 score with a human-readable reason ("Your TNEA cutoff is well above the 70% requirement"), and the weighted total maps to one of four levels: Highly Recommended, Recommended, Suitable, Alternative Option — plus a separate "Over Budget" tag when cost is the actual blocker, so the label tells the student *why*, not just a vague tier.
5. **Hard exclusions happen before scoring**: colleges that don't admit the student's gender, colleges in the wrong subject category entirely (a Law college never shows for a Medical-track student, even if academics/budget look great), and colleges the student's marks are far below cutoff for, are removed from the list completely rather than just scored low — because showing them at all would be misleading.
6. A TF-IDF similarity pass (scikit-learn) gives a small additional boost based on free-text interest matching against course names — this is the one place actual lightweight ML is used in the scoring path itself.

**Course recommendations** work similarly but operate on individual course names parsed out of each college's course list, deduplicated, and scored by whether they match the student's stated interests (with a synonym-expansion map, so "AI" also catches "Machine Learning," "Data Science," "Robotics," etc.) and which colleges offer that course within the student's reach.

If asked **"why not just have the AI do the matching directly"** — this is the question to nail: an LLM doesn't reliably know real cutoff numbers and will fabricate plausible-but-wrong ones. A deterministic engine is auditable (you can always show the exact reason a college appeared) and never invents data.

## Feature 2: Application Tracking

A student can click "Apply" on any recommended college, which creates an application record starting at "Application Started." The student can self-advance it to "Application Submitted," but every later stage — Under Review, Admission Offered, Admission Confirmed, Rejected — can only be set by their assigned counselor. That's a deliberate access-control decision: a student shouldn't be able to mark themselves "Admitted."

## Feature 3: Document Upload

Mark sheets and certificates upload to Supabase Storage (not the database directly — files live in object storage, only metadata like filename and type live in Postgres). Downloads use short-lived signed URLs (5 minutes) rather than public links, since these are personal documents.

## Feature 4: Counselor–Student Messaging

A simple threaded messaging system scoped strictly to assigned pairs — a counselor can only message students actually assigned to them (checked server-side on every request, not just hidden in the UI), with read-receipts and an unread-count badge.

## Feature 5: AI Chatbot, Scholarships, Learning Path

These three are where Groq actually gets used — open-ended, conversational outputs. The chatbot is instructed to ask for missing academic info rather than guess at recommendations with no data. Scholarships and Learning Path take the student's full profile and ask the LLM to generate India-specific, realistic suggestions, formatted into structured sections the frontend can render nicely (not just a wall of text).

**"Why CSV instead of AI knowing the colleges?"**
"AI can guess wrong on real facts like cutoffs — that's risky for something this important. So I used a fixed, verified dataset instead, to make sure the numbers are always accurate."

**"Why aren't colleges recommended by AI directly?"**
"Matching cutoffs is just math — comparing numbers — so I used plain logic for that, since it's always 100% correct. I saved the AI for things that actually need understanding, like answering questions or explaining career options."

**"Can't AI just read the internet and tell?"**
"It can, but that'd be slower, and I can't always trust which website it's pulling from. A fixed, checked dataset is faster and more reliable than the AI re-searching the same facts every time."